WEBVTT

00:00:01.120 --> 00:00:03.480
how do you make a film that teaches

00:00:03.480 --> 00:00:05.120
people about

00:00:05.120 --> 00:00:07.160
science I think it's an important

00:00:07.160 --> 00:00:09.719
question and I think it's a timely

00:00:09.719 --> 00:00:12.320
question given that while video is

00:00:12.320 --> 00:00:14.519
exploding everywhere on the internet and

00:00:14.519 --> 00:00:16.400
there are new initiatives popping up

00:00:16.400 --> 00:00:19.840
like Ted Ed now this question how do you

00:00:19.840 --> 00:00:22.519
make a film that effectively teaches

00:00:22.519 --> 00:00:24.480
someone something about science that was

00:00:24.480 --> 00:00:26.439
the topic of my

00:00:26.439 --> 00:00:29.480
PhD so I'd like to tell you what I found

00:00:29.480 --> 00:00:30.679
out

00:00:30.679 --> 00:00:32.439
I went to the University of Sydney and I

00:00:32.439 --> 00:00:34.960
took all the firste physics students and

00:00:34.960 --> 00:00:37.200
I tried to teach them about the basic

00:00:37.200 --> 00:00:40.160
laws of motion Newton's first and second

00:00:40.160 --> 00:00:43.120
laws so I sent them away to their homes

00:00:43.120 --> 00:00:45.640
and I asked them to go online and sit a

00:00:45.640 --> 00:00:50.160
26 question multiple choice uh test

00:00:50.160 --> 00:00:52.039
here's a sample question just so you get

00:00:52.039 --> 00:00:53.640
a feel for what I was asking them

00:00:53.640 --> 00:00:55.320
imagine a basketball player shooting

00:00:55.320 --> 00:00:57.359
from the free throw line after he

00:00:57.359 --> 00:00:59.440
releases the ball the forces on the ball

00:00:59.440 --> 00:01:03.399
are a a upwards and constant B upwards

00:01:03.399 --> 00:01:07.000
and decreasing C downwards and constant

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:10.960
D downwards and decreasing or E tangent

00:01:10.960 --> 00:01:12.560
to the path of the

00:01:12.560 --> 00:01:14.799
ball I want you to take a minute and

00:01:14.799 --> 00:01:16.320
think

00:01:16.320 --> 00:01:18.520
about think about what you would answer

00:01:18.520 --> 00:01:20.040
and think about think about what you

00:01:20.040 --> 00:01:23.040
think other people might answer okay so

00:01:23.040 --> 00:01:24.799
then we would get the students to rate

00:01:24.799 --> 00:01:26.560
their confidence in their answers how

00:01:26.560 --> 00:01:30.119
confident are you that this is correct

00:01:30.119 --> 00:01:31.600
I should mention that that is not the

00:01:31.600 --> 00:01:33.479
exact lyit scale that I gave them but

00:01:33.479 --> 00:01:36.320
it's you know get the idea across okay

00:01:36.320 --> 00:01:38.680
and then I would randomly assign these

00:01:38.680 --> 00:01:41.119
students uh to watch one of several

00:01:41.119 --> 00:01:42.880
videos about Newton's first and second

00:01:42.880 --> 00:01:45.079
laws they lasted about 8 to 10 minutes

00:01:45.079 --> 00:01:48.360
so in a standard uh Exposition video I

00:01:48.360 --> 00:01:49.719
would say something like this to them

00:01:49.719 --> 00:01:51.880
well we would state Newton's laws and

00:01:51.880 --> 00:01:53.640
then we would apply it to a real world

00:01:53.640 --> 00:01:56.000
example like a juggler I can't juggle so

00:01:56.000 --> 00:01:58.759
I've got one ball anyway um so we would

00:01:58.759 --> 00:02:00.600
say something like while ball is in the

00:02:00.600 --> 00:02:03.000
air there's only one force acting on it

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:04.960
throughout its flight it's a force of

00:02:04.960 --> 00:02:08.160
gravity it's constant and it's downwards

00:02:08.160 --> 00:02:10.319
we'd actually animate a little arrow on

00:02:10.319 --> 00:02:12.760
the ball as it goes up and down in slow

00:02:12.760 --> 00:02:14.680
motion okay so obviously the answer was

00:02:14.680 --> 00:02:17.840
C whereas most people usually pick B to

00:02:17.840 --> 00:02:19.959
that question okay so after watching

00:02:19.959 --> 00:02:22.000
this video the students would sit the

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:25.080
exact same 26 question test I wanted to

00:02:25.080 --> 00:02:27.000
see have they changed their minds about

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:28.640
any of those questions and I also

00:02:28.640 --> 00:02:30.640
interviewed a couple students to see

00:02:30.640 --> 00:02:32.400
what did they think about the video did

00:02:32.400 --> 00:02:33.560
they like it did they think that they

00:02:33.560 --> 00:02:35.480
learned something from it and here's

00:02:35.480 --> 00:02:37.640
what they told me well they said Derek

00:02:37.640 --> 00:02:39.519
that was a great video it was clear

00:02:39.519 --> 00:02:40.680
these are the most common things they

00:02:40.680 --> 00:02:43.319
said it was clear it was concise it was

00:02:43.319 --> 00:02:45.080
easy to

00:02:45.080 --> 00:02:48.159
understand that's good and then I looked

00:02:48.159 --> 00:02:50.519
at their confidence scores how did that

00:02:50.519 --> 00:02:52.640
change on average well on average it

00:02:52.640 --> 00:02:54.879
improved by about a point okay

00:02:54.879 --> 00:02:56.599
everything's looking good but how much

00:02:56.599 --> 00:02:57.560
did they

00:02:57.560 --> 00:02:59.840
learn well on the preest they scored

00:02:59.840 --> 00:03:02.640
scored six out of

00:03:02.640 --> 00:03:04.599
26 and I can tell you there were

00:03:04.599 --> 00:03:06.519
basically direct answers to at least 14

00:03:06.519 --> 00:03:07.920
of those questions but how much did they

00:03:07.920 --> 00:03:11.879
pick up the average on the post test

00:03:11.879 --> 00:03:14.879
was

00:03:15.879 --> 00:03:19.040
6.3 what

00:03:19.040 --> 00:03:22.080
happened they thought they learned but

00:03:22.080 --> 00:03:24.040
their scores didn't change well one of

00:03:24.040 --> 00:03:25.840
the students told me in the video it

00:03:25.840 --> 00:03:28.720
said the ball is slowly decreasing in

00:03:28.720 --> 00:03:31.040
force they thought there was some upward

00:03:31.040 --> 00:03:32.319
force in the ball and they thought that

00:03:32.319 --> 00:03:34.920
was presented to them they couldn't even

00:03:34.920 --> 00:03:36.680
correctly remember what was presented

00:03:36.680 --> 00:03:38.640
five minutes earlier and I had sat in

00:03:38.640 --> 00:03:41.080
the room with them and they watched the

00:03:41.080 --> 00:03:44.599
video the thing is in science students

00:03:44.599 --> 00:03:47.360
don't know nothing about what we trying

00:03:47.360 --> 00:03:49.720
to teach them they actually know lots of

00:03:49.720 --> 00:03:51.239
things through their interaction with

00:03:51.239 --> 00:03:53.280
the world it just turns out that these

00:03:53.280 --> 00:03:56.760
things are wrong scientifically

00:03:56.760 --> 00:03:59.799
speaking so when you present something

00:03:59.799 --> 00:04:01.959
the student thinks they already know it

00:04:01.959 --> 00:04:03.319
and they don't really pay utmost

00:04:03.319 --> 00:04:05.519
attention they don't realize that what's

00:04:05.519 --> 00:04:07.360
being presented differs from their prior

00:04:07.360 --> 00:04:08.519
knowledge and they just get more

00:04:08.519 --> 00:04:10.280
confident in those things that they were

00:04:10.280 --> 00:04:13.280
thinking beforehand so actually a clear

00:04:13.280 --> 00:04:15.959
expository summary is worse than no

00:04:15.959 --> 00:04:18.440
instruction at

00:04:18.440 --> 00:04:21.280
all I mean that very seriously so so how

00:04:21.280 --> 00:04:22.759
do you get students to engage well I

00:04:22.759 --> 00:04:24.840
tried a different approach I put two

00:04:24.840 --> 00:04:27.240
people in a video and I got one to voice

00:04:27.240 --> 00:04:30.479
the common misconceptions

00:04:30.479 --> 00:04:32.280
and then the the tutor would kind of

00:04:32.280 --> 00:04:34.120
indicate okay that's not quite right and

00:04:34.120 --> 00:04:35.960
they would work it out through a social

00:04:35.960 --> 00:04:37.400
dialogue but I mean we would even

00:04:37.400 --> 00:04:39.720
animate the misconception on the ball

00:04:39.720 --> 00:04:40.759
without telling anyone it was a

00:04:40.759 --> 00:04:42.320
misconception they had to work that out

00:04:42.320 --> 00:04:44.080
through the social interaction okay so

00:04:44.080 --> 00:04:45.520
this was the the very same setting that

00:04:45.520 --> 00:04:47.080
every that the other students watched

00:04:47.080 --> 00:04:48.840
the exposition video what did the

00:04:48.840 --> 00:04:51.560
dialogue students say well no one told

00:04:51.560 --> 00:04:53.880
me that it was clear no one told me it

00:04:53.880 --> 00:04:56.160
was concise no one said it was easy to

00:04:56.160 --> 00:04:58.400
understand in fact most of the time they

00:04:58.400 --> 00:05:01.919
told me it was

00:05:02.400 --> 00:05:04.960
confusing man maybe this

00:05:04.960 --> 00:05:07.520
backfired so how' they go on the post

00:05:07.520 --> 00:05:11.000
test well their scores nearly doubled to

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:13.240
11 out of

00:05:13.240 --> 00:05:17.639
26 okay it's not 26 out of 26 but it's a

00:05:17.639 --> 00:05:19.840
start and what was the

00:05:19.840 --> 00:05:22.319
difference well after the video I asked

00:05:22.319 --> 00:05:25.120
students to rate their mental effort how

00:05:25.120 --> 00:05:26.919
much mental effort did you expend while

00:05:26.919 --> 00:05:28.639
watching that

00:05:28.639 --> 00:05:30.560
video and the students who watched the

00:05:30.560 --> 00:05:33.080
dialogue invested significantly more

00:05:33.080 --> 00:05:34.600
mental effort in engaging with that

00:05:34.600 --> 00:05:36.680
presentation than students who saw only

00:05:36.680 --> 00:05:39.120
an expository

00:05:39.120 --> 00:05:41.400
summary so to me there's a really

00:05:41.400 --> 00:05:44.000
important message there depending on how

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:46.479
you present you can change how your

00:05:46.479 --> 00:05:49.440
audience watches and thereby how much

00:05:49.440 --> 00:05:50.680
they

00:05:50.680 --> 00:05:53.400
learn and I'm now applying this I've got

00:05:53.400 --> 00:05:55.759
a YouTube channel it's called

00:05:55.759 --> 00:05:57.919
veritasium and I've made nearly a

00:05:57.919 --> 00:06:00.120
hundred films which have been seen over

00:06:00.120 --> 00:06:03.759
4.5 million times throughout the world

00:06:03.759 --> 00:06:06.199
and you know you always have to start

00:06:06.199 --> 00:06:07.199
with the

00:06:07.199 --> 00:06:11.400
misconceptions thank you

00:06:11.540 --> 00:06:19.479
[Music]
